        "text": "Erdős Problem #750 remains OPEN. Statement: Let $f(m)$ be some function such that $f(m)\\to \\infty$ as $m\\to \\infty$. Does there exist a graph $G$ of infinite chromatic number such that every subgraph on $m$ vertices contains an independent set of size at least $\\frac{m}{2}-f(m)$? Note that in [Er94b] the function $f$ generalises a (proven) result for $f(m) = \\epsilon m$, where $\\epsilon > 0$. Hence we should assume it is non-negative valued. Topics: graph theory, chromatic number. Erdős prize: no. Statement is machine-verified in Lean (formal-conjectures). OEIS: N/A.",
